# Contributing to Nigerian ANPR System

First off, thank you for considering contributing to the Nigerian ANPR System! It's people like you that make this project better.

##  Code of Conduct

This project and everyone participating in it is governed by respect and professionalism. By participating, you are expected to uphold this standard.

##  How to Report a Bug

**Before submitting a bug report:**
- Check the [Issues](https://github.com/Alpha-dev-001/Nigeria_anpr_python/issues) to see if the problem has already been reported
- Check the [Troubleshooting section](README.md#-troubleshooting) in the README

**When submitting a bug report, include:**
- A clear, descriptive title
- Steps to reproduce the issue
- Expected behavior vs actual behavior
- Screenshots if applicable
- Your environment:
  - OS (Windows/Linux/Mac)
  - Python version
  - GPU (if using GPU acceleration)
  - Camera type and resolution
- Relevant config.py settings
- Console output/error messages

##  How to Suggest a Feature

**Before suggesting a feature:**
- Check if the feature already exists
- Check the [Issues](https://github.com/Alpha-dev-001/Nigeria_anpr_python/issues) to see if someone already suggested it

**When suggesting a feature, describe:**
- The problem it solves
- How it should work
- Why it would be useful to most users
- Any alternative solutions you've considered

##  How to Submit Changes

### Development Workflow

1. **Fork the repository**
   ```bash
   git clone https://github.com/YOUR-USERNAME/Nigeria_anpr_python.git
   cd Nigeria_anpr_python
   ```

2. **Create a branch**
   ```bash
   git checkout -b feature/your-feature-name
   ```

3. **Make your changes**
   - Write clear, commented code
   - Follow the existing code style
   - Update documentation if needed
   - Test your changes thoroughly

4. **Commit your changes**
   ```bash
   git add .
   git commit -m "Add: Brief description of your changes"
   ```
   
   **Commit message format:**
   - `Add:` for new features
   - `Fix:` for bug fixes
   - `Update:` for updates to existing features
   - `Docs:` for documentation changes
   - `Refactor:` for code refactoring
   - `Test:` for test-related changes

5. **Push to your fork**
   ```bash
   git push origin feature/your-feature-name
   ```

6. **Create a Pull Request**
   - Go to the original repository
   - Click "New Pull Request"
   - Select your fork and branch
   - Fill in the PR template

### Pull Request Guidelines

**Your PR should:**
- Have a clear title describing what it does
- Reference any related issues (e.g., "Fixes #123")
- Include a description of changes
- Include screenshots/videos for UI changes
- Pass all existing tests
- Not break existing functionality

**Code quality standards:**
- Follow PEP 8 for Python code
- Use meaningful variable and function names
- Add comments for complex logic
- Keep functions focused and concise
- Avoid hardcoded values (use config.py)

##  Priority Areas for Contribution

We especially welcome contributions in these areas:

### High Priority
- [ ] **Multi-camera support** - Handle multiple camera feeds simultaneously
- [ ] **Docker containerization** - Easy deployment via Docker
- [ ] **Export functionality** - Generate PDF/Excel reports
- [ ] **Real-time alerts** - Email/SMS notifications for specific events
- [ ] **Performance optimization** - Improve OCR speed and accuracy

### Medium Priority
- [ ] **Mobile dashboard** - Responsive mobile app or PWA
- [ ] **Cloud deployment guides** - AWS/Azure/GCP setup instructions
- [ ] **Additional African plate formats** - Support for other countries
- [ ] **Advanced analytics** - Traffic flow analysis, peak times, etc.
- [ ] **User authentication** - Login system for the dashboard

### Low Priority
- [ ] **Theme customization** - Dark mode, custom colors
- [ ] **Backup/restore** - Database backup functionality
- [ ] **API documentation** - OpenAPI/Swagger docs
- [ ] **Internationalization** - Multi-language support

##  Style Guide

### Python Code Style
- Follow [PEP 8](https://pep8.org/)
- Use 4 spaces for indentation (no tabs)
- Maximum line length: 100 characters
- Use docstrings for functions and classes

```python
def example_function(param1, param2):
    """
    Brief description of what the function does.
    
    Args:
        param1 (type): Description of param1
        param2 (type): Description of param2
    
    Returns:
        type: Description of return value
    """
    # Implementation here
    pass
```

### JavaScript/HTML Style
- Use 2 spaces for indentation
- Use semicolons
- Use camelCase for variables
- Use meaningful variable names

### Git Commit Messages
- Use the present tense ("Add feature" not "Added feature")
- Use the imperative mood ("Move cursor to..." not "Moves cursor to...")
- Limit the first line to 72 characters
- Reference issues and pull requests

##  Testing

Before submitting a PR, test your changes:

1. **Basic functionality test:**
   ```bash
   python anpr_system.py
   ```
   - Ensure camera connects
   - Verify plates are detected
   - Check state recognition works
   - Confirm database logging

2. **Dashboard test:**
   ```bash
   python web_interface.py
   ```
   - Visit http://localhost:5000
   - Check all panels load
   - Verify data refreshes
   - Test search functionality
   - Click vehicle modal works

3. **Integration test:**
   ```bash
   python launcher.py
   ```
   - Both systems start correctly
   - Browser opens automatically
   - Data flows from detection to dashboard

##  Documentation

When adding new features, update:
- [ ] README.md (if user-facing)
- [ ] config.py comments (if adding new config)
- [ ] Code comments (for complex logic)
- [ ] ANPR_System_Documentation.docx (for major features)

##  Questions?

If you have questions about contributing:
- Check existing [Issues](https://github.com/Alpha-dev-001/Nigeria_anpr_python/issues)
- Open a new issue with the "question" label
- Reach out to the maintainers

##  Recognition

Contributors will be:
- Listed in the repository contributors page
- Acknowledged in release notes for major contributions
- Given credit in the documentation for significant features

##  License

By contributing, you agree that your contributions will be licensed under the same license as the project (MIT License).

---

Thank you for making this project better! 